TO CONTINUE OUR DISCUSSION<br><br>
Jed<br>
Re: Post above, your statements my response<br>
1. One of the major reasons for going into the war was to stop the spread of communism.<br><br>
Response:That WAS the main reason we entered into the Vietnam conflict, Kennedy knew that we had failed to stop the spread of communism in Laos and because he had failed again to consult his military advisors, before making decision (similar to the bay of Pigs fiasco) as a result we settled for a poor agreement with Moscow by which the Pathet Lao Communist Terrorist organization was allowed to stay in Laos in the eastern half of the country. I recall during our military training that we were trained to be prepared battle against those forces, which were then entering into South Vietnam. That area that later was used to move North Vietnamese troops and supplies into South Vietnam. It was the classic Communist plan of two steps forward, one step backwards, and they had obtained their foothold in South East Asia. Laos and Cambodia continue to suffer from that major Kennedy blunder because he failed to consult his military advisors and turned instead to his intellectual ‘wiz kids’, as they were known in Washington.<br><br>
2. U.S. govt. economic policy required countries to supply raw materials including cheap labor for our economic expansion. <br><br>
Response:Wow, what a statement, sounds a lot like the propaganda distributed by anti-America left wing radicals of the 60’s, but those are your thoughts. Statements like that we all too often skim over, accept them as truth and move on. Required cheap labor?<br>
Don’t we all shop around for the best bargain? Why pay $17.95 for a sweater at Macy’s when you can buy the same article at Wal-Mart for $7.95.<br><br>
3. Communism threatened our ability to get raw goods cheap and have access to get the wealth of<br>
Other countries without having to pay top dollar. <br><br>
Response:  Ok, let’s pay top dollar. Let’s pay more taxes, for goods from other third world countries, but would that stop Communist slave camps? No, they would only increase with the top communist forces enjoying the wealth while the people suffer.<br><br>
4. Vietnam was one country and their main interest was in reunification and the elimination of foreign dominance in their internal affairs. <br><br>
Response: That, we know has not happened, Vietnam wanted to be left alone. Vietnam before the 1959 division was not a united Communist country. It is today. They lost all their freedom, During the war all educators, writers, poets, artist in THE NORTH had to go underground or they would be send to re-education camps. I did what I could. <br><br>
Both the Russians and Chinese wanted Vietnams harbors, Uncle Ho chose Moscow. Meanwhile the Chinese certainly did not want Russia at their front door and entered into the fray in support of a communist take over of the South by Ho Chi Minh, this was done long before we got militarily involved.<br>
China believed that after the war Vietnam would be weak, they would have their advisors in place there and that would enable them to slip in through the backdoor and completely take over Vietnam. <br><br>
5. That is one reason that China was always less of a supporter of N. Vietnam than other communist countries. The Vietnamese have been fighting against Chinese control of Vietnam for thousands of years.<br><br>
Response:The Chinese communist were heavily involved in the Vietnam War. In 1941 Ho Chi Minh who had been living in Moscow returned to Vietnam after a 30-year absence. He was send there by the Soviet Union as their puppet. He was send there for the unification of Vietnam under Communist rule. Ho led the struggle against the Japanese, then against the French; under the banner of unification and false promises. Communist China equipped all his Vietminh soldiers. But Ho’s devotion was to mother Russia; Ho was part of a Soviet-sponsored, monolithic Communist movement. He could care less of his fellow countrymen willing to sacrifice 10 to 1 in order to establish a communist state. Ho used both China and Russia and in the process destroyed the country of his birth, he betrayed them for political power, he was a traitor to his fellow countrymen and they have suffered for his selfish ambitions ever since. They continue that struggle against communistic principles today; the resent November 1997 uprising is present evidence of that. <br>
When Ho Chi Minh came into power he established his own communist ruling party and that minor 8% of avowed Communist still rule that country with an iron fist. <br>
Vietnam today is one county, it is united but it is not the Vietnam the people want. They still want to be free of communistic principles and domination. <br>
Many in the North during the war would have welcomed us as liberators had we ventured that way. A ticket parade would have greeted us had we done so, &quot;Welcome the conquering heroes,&quot; would have been shouted for the US in the streets of Hanoi. But Johnson was afraid of China’s intervention and what Russia and China would do if we moved north. <br>
China certainly did not want a US presence in Vietnam that is why they supported a divided Vietnam in the late 50's and in the early 70's. Meanwhile their two steps forward, one step back took another two steps forward as soon as the US presence left Vietnam and the country lost its freedom. <br>
That is what I see protesting the war in Vietnam accomplished.<br>

